Consumer in Java

Consumer is a functional interface that takes one input and returns nothing.

👉 It is used when you want to consume/use data without returning a result.

Syntax
Consumer<T>

👉 where T — тип входного значения

Basic Example
import java.util.function.Consumer;

Consumer<String> print = x -> System.out.println(x);

print.accept("Hello");
Main Method
accept()
consumer.accept(value);

👉 takes a value and performs some action

Example with List
List<String> list = List.of("Apple", "Banana", "Orange");

list.forEach(x -> System.out.println(x));

👉 forEach() uses Consumer

Chaining Consumers
andThen()
Consumer<String> first = x -> System.out.println(x);
Consumer<String> second = x -> System.out.println(x.toUpperCase());

Consumer<String> combined = first.andThen(second);

combined.accept("hello");
Real Use Cases
printing data
logging
updating objects
processing collections
Consumer vs Other Interfaces
Interface	Input	Output
Predicate	1	boolean
Function	1	value
Consumer	1	void
Supplier	0	value
Important Note

👉 Consumer changes or uses data, but does NOT return anything.

Example with Object
Consumer<List<String>> addItem = list -> list.add("Apple");

List<String> fruits = new ArrayList<>();

addItem.accept(fruits);

System.out.println(fruits);
Why use Consumer?
cleaner functional-style code
useful in streams and collections
perfect for actions without return value
Summary
Consumer takes input and returns nothing
main method: accept()
often used with forEach()
useful for processing and actions
